John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results have demonstrated individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other societally important disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are trained across Scotland, and where they aim to provide the highest level of service for students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for further higher education, their chosen careers, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector that is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school program, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you turn to his heart.”
This is a compelling proof that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams this year, we see that languages occupy the leading positions in the league tables and have the highest scores in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade of “A”.
Data from 74 SCIS-member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an “A” in Mandarin (a Chinese term), while 72 percent of students studied German, 69 percent also received a “A” in French, and 63 percent received a “A” in French.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and in other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 per cent of the reasons for employers’ difficulties in filling vacancies were due to a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the backbone of a successful future career for young people.
Given that more forward-looking jobs require language skills, these skills are necessary in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will benefit him throughout his further life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
That’s why investing in language education is so relevant right now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland there is quite a large spread in terms of languages that are taught – each school has its own set of languages.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in light of the country’s future development by 2020 — such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, in independent schools there will always be a choice of several languages with a teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Scotland’s independent schools strive to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future development of the country, and that this should be reflected accordingly in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, which will provide diversity and benefits to the youth of Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edwards, Director of the Council of Independent Schools of Scotland
