North Korea says it will not “categorically” disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are heightening distrust of the United States and that its country will under no circumstances give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial measures of goodwill” last year, such as the cessation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of nuclear facilities and the commitment not to increase nuclear and non-nuclear stockpiles.
“However, we do not observe a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be the first to unilaterally take action on disarmament.”
While Ri reiterated the already-sounding North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to the “stage” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea will be rewarded for its gradual steps in the past, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not deny.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit in history between the current US president and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start the movement towards “the diary.”
North Korea is seeking to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington is also opposed to calls for a weakening of tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearization must be done first,’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions in order to enforce its goal, and even opposes ‘the declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri says.
“The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions are intensifying our distrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Zhe Yin over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea, not the United States, were the denuclearization side of the denuclearization issue.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech differed sharply from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim “a suicide bomber.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much more to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disbands.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not specify any timelines for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang to take the steps that have been taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council’s imposition of sanctions must continue actively and obligatoryly until we see a complete, definitive and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006, with a view to curtailing the funding of Pyongyang ' s nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and said after that meeting that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but within hours of that visit, North Korea condemned him for “bandit demands.”
North Korea has pledged at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile complex as well as the nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate action” on its part.
According to him, Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he was talking about were security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore, as well as actions aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
