Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he came up with the idea of introducing such a course, giving a preliminary report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl approached me and said, ‘I’m so sorry I only learned about it now that I’m almost done with my studies.’
She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how the habit of healthy sleep contributes to academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university has decided to introduce this course after it was found that students are experiencing severe sleep deprivation during non-education.
The lesson lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections of the class is offered an image of the room in the dormitory, where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, gymnastics and books, receive information about how each of these actions and substances are important to the effect of the results of the consumption of coffee, light, and sleep deprivation.
In another section, participants will learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
