A new study, conducted in one of the Scottish Hills, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It should be hoped that the data obtained will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and help in further activities to preserve the species.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland, will study ordinary non-powder, non-powder soprano, as well as brown long-haired bats and Dobanton nights inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to track the actions of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile field surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the types of activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report will be prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewear, an NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the main areas of work on habitat management, such as meadow formation, as well as ways to maintain the forest massifs in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk of disappearance due to construction and development work, which affect their habitat and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose a danger as well as adhesive tape for flies, chemical processing of building materials and hunting of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use complex echo-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles in the way of flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, is very serious about bat population issues.
The organization employs ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, outbound checks, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization even created Scotland’s first and only reservation of bats at the Thrave estate in Damfries and Galloway, home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
Real estate manager David Thompson says the property is the perfect territory for them.
“Here in Thrave, it’s a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, many old trees and all the elements of a good living environment.
But much remains unknown about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need for a healthy existence.”
It recalls the importance of checking the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance within private property, since the accidental destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Flying mice are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitat is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Flea Conservation Foundation, is calling on the public to help.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of their individual species live.”
